@@eRoc Road -- Kiess Convoy Marshal Standing Brief@@N

Every convoy marshal receives this brief before their first departure
from the western gate. Roc Road is not merely our trade route. It is
our @@ylifeline@@N, our founding scar, and Evermeet's ghost made visible
in every milestone from here to Midgaard.

On the @@ywestern half@@N, Kiess convoy marshals manage actual flow. Our
@@yconvoy compacts@@N are shared liability pools that distribute losses
across all participants. A marshal can delay departures during threat
spikes, reroute through the @@gGreenveil Spur@@N, and authorize emergency
payments to wayfolk for guide services. This is @@yfunctional logistics@@N:
what keeps goods and people alive to arrive tomorrow.

On the @@Weastern half@@N, Midgaard's imprint is carved in stone: ash-
mortar paving, patrol relays, checkpoint oath recitations, and the
@@WThree Civic Oaths@@N at every shift change. Boundary sigils repainted
even when manpower prevents full repairs. The Syndics note this
without mockery -- Midgaard's system works for Midgaard. But a
repainted sigil does not fill a pothole, and an oath does not feed
a stranded convoy.

The central @@rCrossroads@@N is where both systems blur and independent
actors arbitrage disagreement. Violence spikes whenever one side
attempts unilateral control. Our marshals carry Syndic warrants for
the Crossroads -- and yes, we appreciate the irony. These warrants
@@yexpire@@N. They are renewed or they die. That is the difference
between a Kiess warrant and a @@rsealed@@N one.

The @@dViolet Eclipse Cathedral@@N along the route predates both cities.
Marshals are instructed to trade there if necessary, observe always,
and trust nothing that cannot be verified at the Prism.

Evermeet's ghost walks Roc Road in the crumbling foundations at the
@@dfourth western milestone@@N, in obsidian shards that surface after
heavy rain, in the silence where a city's noise once carried. The
road runs through four historical strata beneath our boots -- each
power repaired what it needed and ignored the rest. We do the same,
but we are honest about it.

@@yWhere Midgaard asks "Who has lawful right to command?" Kiess asks
"What keeps goods and people alive to arrive tomorrow?"@@N The road's
identity is built from that unresolved argument. Every marshal
carries both questions. The good ones never stop asking.
